    {
        "control_id": "NETWORK_004",
        "control_name": "Web application firewall (WAF)",
        "vodafone_standard": "Tier 3 Web Application Firewall (WAF) [CYBER/STD/043] MR1",
        "domain": "Network",
        "d_statements": [
            {"id": "D1", "text": "TLS Decryption: The WAF solution must perform TLS decryption to inspect encrypted traffic up to the latest version (TLS 1.3 as of April 2020 or higher)."},
            {"id": "D2", "text": "HTTP Conformity: The WAF solution must verify HTTP traffic conformity to the HTTP standard up to the latest version (including HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 or higher)"},
            {"id": "D4", "text": "The WAF solution must accurately detect and block session (cookie) injection attacks according to A07:2021 - Identification and Authentication Failures."},
            {"id": "D5", "text": "The WAF solution must accurately detect and block XML External Entities (XXE) attacks according to OWASP Top 10 A05:2021 - Security Misconfiguration"},
            {"id": "D6", "text": "The WAF solution must accurately detect and block Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) according to OWASP Top Ten A03:2021 – Injection."},
            {"id": "D7", "text": "The WAF solution must accurately detect and block deserialization attacks (for more information please refer to OWASP Top Ten A08:2021-Software and Data Integrity Failures)."},
            {"id": "D8", "text": "The WAF solution must be configured to mitigate attacks that exploit vulnerable third-party components of web applications according to OWASP Top Ten A06:2021 - Vulnerable and Outdated Components"},
            {"id": "D9", "text": "OWASP Top Ten: The WAF solution must protect any on-boarded web application against the remaining Open Web Application Security Project (OWASP) Top Ten attacks:  A01:2021-Broken Access Control; A02:2021-Cryptographic Failures;   A05:2021-Security Misconfiguration (excluding XSS covered by D6);   and new 2021 categories:   A04:2021-Insecure Design;   A08:2021-Software and Data Integrity Failures (excluding insecure deserialization covered by D7); and   A10:2021-Server-Side Request Forgery"},
            {"id": "D10", "text": "Logging & Monitoring: The WAF solution must be capable to send both security and system events via secure protocols to a SIEM system, analytics tool, syslog server or any cloud-based log monitoring solution (for more information please refer to OWASP Top Ten A09:2021 - Security Logging and Monitoring Failures."},
            {"id": "D11", "text": "Policies & Signatures Update: All WAF platforms must be uniformly, consistently and promptly updated with new signatures and policies released by the supplier.    Negative Model: The WAF solution supports and enforces a negative security model."},
            {"id": "D12", "text": "Bot Mitigation: The WAF solution must accurately detect and block attacks coming from malicious bots. In particular, the WAF solution must protect the company's main websites - e.g. websites where customers make bill payments or purchases - from Account Takeover attacks."},
            {"id": "D13", "text": "Private Keys Protection: The WAF solution must ensure that any application's private key stored within the WAF itself is protected from unauthorized access."},
            {"id": "D14", "text": "Encoded & Compressed Payload Protection: The WAF solution must inspect traffic with encoded or compressed payload in order to prevent evasion techniques."},
            {"id": "D15", "text": "Sensitive Data Protection and GDPR  The WAF solution must detect and prevent the leakage of sensitive data, such as social security numbers, account balances, PINs, passwords, and other personally identifiable information (PII)."},
            {"id": "D16", "text": "Management Portal Access Control  The WAF solution must be manageable through a self-service management portal that supports Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) or via a configuration API."},
            {"id": "D17", "text": "Positive Model   The traditional appliance-based WAF solution must support and enforce a positive security model, allowing only traffic that meets predefined criteria."},
            {"id": "D18", "text": "Cloud WAF Content Delivery Network (CDN)  The Cloud WAF solution must utilize globally distributed points of presence (PoPs)."},
            {"id": "D19", "text": "Cloud WAF Data Residency  The Cloud WAF solution must be able to meet local data residency requirements, if mandated."},
            {"id": "D20", "text": "Origin IP Allowlisting,Firewall Rules and Security Groups  The origin servers should only accept traffic from the Cloud WAF’s IP addresses.   Strict firewall rules must block all traffic from IP addresses not associated with the Cloud WAF. Security groups in cloud environments (like AWS, Azure, GCP) must allow traffic only from the WAF IP range."},
            {"id": "D21", "text": "DNS security  DNS records must point exclusively to the Cloud WAF."},
        ],
        "e_statements": [
            {"id": "E1", "text": "Central: Screenshots showing configuration of TLS decryption and any links to the relevant support documentation."},
            {"id": "E2", "text": "Central: Screenshot showing the configuration of HTTP/2.  Screenshot showing the configuration of HTTP/3."},
            {"id": "E3", "text": "Central: Evidence of WAF configuration to detect injection attacks. Positive input validation enabled. Samples of logs showing attacks being blocked."},
            {"id": "E4", "text": "Central: Evidence of WAF configuration to validate session tokens (cookies). Sample of logs showing session injection attacks being blocked."},
            {"id": "E5", "text": "Central: Sample of configuration and logs showing XXE attacks being blocked."},
            {"id": "E6", "text": "Central: Sample of configuration and logs showing XXS is blocked."},
            {"id": "E7", "text": "Central: Evidence of configuration and logs showing deserialization attacks are blocked."},
            {"id": "E8", "text": "Central: Evidence of configuration and logs showing that exploits in third-party components are prevented."},
            {"id": "E9", "text": "Central: Evidence showing that remaining OWASP attacks are being prevented."},
            {"id": "E10", "text": "Central: Evidence of configuration for WAF sending system and security event logs to a SIEM OR evidence of WAFs onboarded into SIEMs."},
            {"id": "E11", "text": "Central: Evidence of latest update applied to the WAF and that it is in line with the latest update from the supplier.  Central: Logs showing blocking of malicious traffic based on signatures and policies applied."},
            {"id": "E12", "text": "Central: Evidence of configuration blocking malicious bots and logs showing that the block is effective."},
            {"id": "E13", "text": "Central: Evidence demonstrating protection in place for private keys or documentation from solution provider in the case of cloud WAF solutions."},
            {"id": "E14", "text": "- Central: Configuration showing that this is enabled for the relevant sites.   - Local Markets/Entity: List of applications requiring this level of protection."},
            {"id": "E15", "text": "Evidence of searches for predefined patterns or masking sensitive data within security events.  Or Documentation showing WAF configuration to identify sensitive data types."},
            {"id": "E16", "text": "RBAC Policy Documentation: Access control policies showing role-based restrictions within the WAF management portal  Evidence of periodic access reviews, ensuring users have the appropriate level of access."},
            {"id": "E17", "text": "Logs that document traffic being blocked due to violations of the positive model (e.g., HTTP method restrictions)."},
            {"id": "E18", "text": "CDN Provider Documentation: Documentation showing that the WAF leverages a CDN with globally distributed points of presence (PoPs)."},
            {"id": "E19", "text": "Where applicable- compliance documentation or certification ensuring the WAF provider complies with local data residency laws."},
            {"id": "E20", "text": "Evidence of IP allowlisting at the origin, restricting access only to Cloud WAF IP addresses.    Logs showing that traffic from non-WAF IPs was blocked or denied access to the origin servers.    Configuration details for firewalls and security groups restricting access only to the Cloud WAF IP range.  Logs showing policy enforcement and blocking of non-WAF IP addresses at both firewall and security group levels."},
            {"id": "E21", "text": "Screenshots or documentation showing DNS records configured to point exclusively to the Cloud WAF."},
        ],
    },
    {
        "control_id": "NETWORK_005",
        "control_name": "Firewall rule base management",
        "vodafone_standard": "",
        "domain": "Network",
        "d_statements": [
            {"id": "D1", "text": "An inventory of all firewalls is in place and kept up-to-date."},
            {"id": "D2", "text": "A firewall policy management solution has connectivity with all firewalls, routers and switches owned and managed by the organisation."},
            {"id": "D3", "text": "A firewall change management process has been documented, approved and published."},
            {"id": "D4", "text": "Prior to implementing firewall rule base changes, a manual or automated security check is being performed which reflects security policies and firewall rule security guidelines."},
            {"id": "D5", "text": "No firewall rule base change is being applied without formal management authorisation."},
            {"id": "D6", "text": "Changes to the firewall rule base are being monitored and recorded."},
            {"id": "D7", "text": "A process / mechanism / reporting is in place to identify firewall rules which haven’t been authorised by management. Any unauthorised rules found are being removed / adjusted in a timely manner followed by a risk assessment."},
            {"id": "D8", "text": "A process / mechanism is in place to identify redundant firewall rules and objects, e.g. shadowed rules, unattached objects, duplicate objects and services, empty groups, redundant and disabled rules and ACLs."},
            {"id": "D9", "text": "Any identified redundant rules, objects and ACLs are being removed as part of a clean-up activity on a regular basis."},
            {"id": "D10", "text": "A process / mechanism is in place to ensure any alerts identified on the firewall policy management solution classified as critical or high are being reviewed and followed-up with an action as required in a timely manner."},
        ],
        "e_statements": [
            {"id": "E1", "text": "Asset inventory documenting all firewalls in use, evidence the inventory is kept up-to-date i.e. revision history."},
            {"id": "E2", "text": "Screenshot from the firewall policy management tool demonstrating that it has connectivity with all firewalls, routers and switches (as applicable) documented in the asset inventory in"},
            {"id": "E3", "text": "Copy of process document for handling firewall changes including risk assessment and testing procedures. Evidence that the process has been reviewed and approved by management (i.e. document revision history) and made available to key stakeholders (i.e. training for personnel in charge of firewall changes)."},
            {"id": "E4", "text": "Copy of firewall change ticket or relevant documentation capturing the outcome of a successful manual or automated security test, to ensure the change complies with security policies and guidelines, prior to implementing the change."},
            {"id": "E5", "text": "Data export or screenshot from the firewall management solution capturing all firewall rule base changes made within the last 30 days. Corresponding screenshot from change management system demonstrating tickets for firewall changes made within the same timeframe. 1 sample change ticket with management authorisation formally documented."},
            {"id": "E6", "text": "Logs from the firewall policy management solution demonstrating that all changes made to the firewall rule base are recorded, including unauthorised changes. This can be the data export or screenshot provided in"},
            {"id": "E7", "text": "Screenshot of change ticket for removing or adjusting the unauthorised rules, including risk assessment output and implementation date, where evidence provided in"},
            {"id": "E8", "text": "Documented outcome of process to review redundant firewall rules, objects and ACLs e.g. data export of all existing rules, business justifications for valid rules, and clear identification of rules to be removed."},
            {"id": "E9", "text": "Screenshot of change ticket for removing redundant rules, objects and ACLs, where evidence provided in"},
            {"id": "E10", "text": "Process documentation for reviewing alerts on the firewall policy management solution. Screenshot of firewall management tool demonstrating that all alerts classified as critical or high are reviewed and closed as appropriate. Screenshots of follow-up measures e.g. incident ticket, corrective actions including changes to firewall rules.  Note: Where no policy management solution exists, verify that there is a process that captures approvals for risky rules (e.g. those that have no specific source/ destination) or use of known insecure protocols."},
        ],
    },
    {
        "control_id": "GENERAL_003",
        "control_name": "Outgoing corporate user web traffic filtering",
        "vodafone_standard": "",
        "domain": "General",
        "d_statements": [
            {"id": "D1", "text": "A website access policy is in place which defines restrictions for users to access the Internet; the policy is updated as required following a formal process which includes approvals from the relevant stakeholders."},
            {"id": "D2", "text": "Access policies get thoroughly tested and implemented."},
            {"id": "D3", "text": "Signatures and detection patterns are tested and installed onto the web security solution as they are received from the vendor base."},
            {"id": "D4", "text": "The web security solution blocks malicious websites and site content according to the defined policy."},
            {"id": "D5", "text": "The web security solution analyses in real-time the content of high risk sites, including scripts, banners, iframes, etc. on the site and files requested to be downloaded."},
            {"id": "D6", "text": "Incoming and outgoing malicious traffic (Trojans, backdoors, other malware) gets blocked and reported on."},
            {"id": "D7", "text": "The web security solution includes multiple analysis engines (signature based and non-signature based scanning) to uncover known and zero-day malicious code."},
            {"id": "D8", "text": "The web security solution is integrated with ArcSight or other SIEM platform."},
            {"id": "D9", "text": "Threat events get logged and threat event reports are being reviewed and appropriate action is being taken in a timely manner."},
            {"id": "D10", "text": "Reports from the web security solution covering threat events and web usage and are being run regularly and the information provided is being acted on."},
            {"id": "D11", "text": "Where personally identifiable information, e.g. user names and end-user IP addresses in URL reports, is collected, it gets obfuscated as required and made available to users of the web security solution and retained following a strict need to know principle."},
            {"id": "D12", "text": "Potentially sensitive evidence captured by the web security solution is protected and access to the web security solution is tightly restricted and monitored to meet privacy requirements and prevent misuse."},
            {"id": "D13", "text": "The web security solution was tested prior to deploying to production and test documentation/results are available."},
            {"id": "D14", "text": "Key documentation to support the web security solution is in place and kept up to date as applicable, e.g. processes and procedures, Service Operation documentation, HLD and LLD."},
        ],
        "e_statements": [
            {"id": "E1", "text": "Copy of policy document which defines restrictions for users to access the internet. Evidence that the policy has been formally reviewed and approved by relevant stakeholders (i.e. document revision history)."},
            {"id": "E2", "text": "Test results or change tickets demonstrating that access policies are tested on pre-production systems prior to deploying to production systems."},
            {"id": "E3", "text": "Screenshot of the solution demonstrating the latest signatures from the vendor base are installed. Evidence demonstrating the signatures are tested on non-production environment prior to being installed on the production environment, e.g. change ticket, process documentation or workflow for standard or pre-approved changes."},
            {"id": "E4", "text": "Screenshot of the web security blocklist for malicious websites and site content. Screenshot of an attempt to access a known malicious website, demonstrating the access is blocked for the user e.g. error messages."},
            {"id": "E5", "text": "Screenshot of the web security or proxy AV solution settings for real-time analysis of site content including scripts, banners, iframes and on file downloads. Screenshot demonstrating action taken when harmful content is found e.g. harmful scripts are blocked from being executed."},
            {"id": "E6", "text": "Screenshot of the web security or proxy AV solution showing that web traffic filtering is configured for incoming and outgoing malicious traffic. Screenshot of quarantined Trojans, backdoors or other malware. Example of reports or alerts raised when malware is found."},
            {"id": "E7", "text": "Screenshot of the web security or proxy AV solution demonstrating that signature based and non-signature based scanning is enabled to uncover known and zero-day malicious code."},
            {"id": "E8", "text": "Screenshot from the web security solution settings demonstrating that alerts are sent to ArcSight or other SIEM platform   OR Screenshot from the SIEM platform demonstrating web security events are being fed into the SIEM platform, and alerts are configured."},
            {"id": "E9", "text": "Logs and reports of threat events from the web security solution. Evidence the threats are reviewed by the security team and appropriate action is taken in a timely manner, e.g. incident tickets, corrective actions, or formal documentation of risk and mitigating controls."},
            {"id": "E10", "text": "Copy of a report from the web security solution covering threat events and web usage. Evidence that the reports are reviewed by management e.g. meeting minutes or trend analysis; and appropriate action is taken based on information provided e.g. tuning of content filtering settings."},
            {"id": "E11", "text": "Excerpts of reports from the web security solution or design documentation demonstrating that personally identifiable information is obfuscated before being made available to users."},
            {"id": "E12", "text": "Screenshot of data classification and handling settings for the web security solution, demonstrating that access to potentially sensitive data is restricted and monitored."},
            {"id": "E13", "text": "Report or test results of web security solution prior to deploying to production. The results should demonstrate that all requirements from security policies and design documents have been met; if exceptions were found, evidence of risk assessment or approval by the security team."},
            {"id": "E14", "text": "Evidence that key web security process and design documents are reviewed and kept up to date, e.g. revision history. Documents are updated with new threats identified from risk assessments and tuning activities."},
        ],
    },
    {
        "control_id": "GENERAL_004",
        "control_name": "Protection of corporate LAN access",
        "vodafone_standard": "",
        "domain": "General",
        "d_statements": [
            {"id": "D1", "text": "A website access policy is in place which defines restrictions for users to access the Internet; the policy is updated as required following a formal process which includes approvals from the relevant stakeholders."},
            {"id": "D2", "text": "For LANs where 802.1x authentication hasn't been enabled, any unused ports and ports in public areas are disabled."},
            {"id": "D3", "text": "For authorised devices access to the local area networks is controlled by using Digital Certificates."},
            {"id": "D4", "text": "The authentication of user devices is performed via 'Mutual certificate authentication' with '802.1x Extensible Authentication Protocol Transport Layer Security (EAP TLS)'."},
            {"id": "D5", "text": "All Digital Certificates used are delivered by the Vodafone Certificate Authority service."},
            {"id": "D6", "text": "All Access Switch Operating Systems are configured to support 802.1x authentication mechanisms."},
            {"id": "D7", "text": "Where devices which are unable to support 802.1x natively need to be authenticated via an alternative method, this method has been formally approved by Cyber Security."},
            {"id": "D8", "text": "Local area network authentication, authorisation and accounting is established in line with Vodafone Global Standards for all clients connecting to the Office LAN."},
            {"id": "D9", "text": "Where authentication to the office LAN environment is denied, the access of that user must be restricted to the Internet via the Guest network."},
            {"id": "D10", "text": "Accounting is performed on 802.1x enabled LANs using Remote Authentication Dial in User Service (RADIUS) accounting records for incident analysis."},
            {"id": "D11", "text": "The configuration of local area networks and Vodafone owned devices prevents any 3rd party devices from successfully connecting to the Vodafone network."},
        ],
        "e_statements": [
            {"id": "E1", "text": "Copy of policy document which defines restrictions for users to access the internet. Evidence that the policy has been formally reviewed and approved by relevant stakeholders (i.e. document revision history)."},
            {"id": "E2", "text": "Screenshot from the network device management system demonstrating that unused ports and ports in public areas are disabled on LANs where 802.1x authentication is not enabled."},
            {"id": "E3", "text": "Screenshot from the network device management system demonstrating that Digital Certificates or PKI are enabled for authorised device access to LANs. Where applicable, screenshot of blocked connections where the device's identity cannot be established i.e. the certificate is invalid."},
            {"id": "E4", "text": "Screenshot of the network device management system settings demonstrating that the authentication of user devices is performed via mutual certificate authentication with 802.1x EAP TLS."},
            {"id": "E5", "text": "Screenshot of a Digital Certificate providing access to corporate LAN issued by the Vodafone Certificate Authority."},
            {"id": "E6", "text": "Screenshot from the network device management system demonstrating that all Access Switch operating systems are upgraded and configured to support 802.1x authentication."},
            {"id": "E7", "text": "Documented approval from Cyber Security where devices which cannot support 802.1x natively and need to be authenticated via an alternative method, e.g. design document or risk register excerpt."},
            {"id": "E8", "text": "Evidence that LAN authentication, authorisation and accounting settings are established in line with Vodafone Global Standards e.g. security assessment or test report. Where gaps are found, they are either fixed or documented as exceptions and approved."},
            {"id": "E9", "text": "Process, configuration settings, or workflow demonstrating that where authentication to the office LAN environment is denied then that user will only be allowed to connect to the Internet via the Guest network, either via the WiFi Guest Service Set Identifier (SSID) or by being assigned to a guest/restricted virtual LAN (VLAN)."},
            {"id": "E10", "text": "Screenshot of RADIUS accounting records demonstrating that authentication activity on 802.1x enabled LANs is recorded."},
            {"id": "E11", "text": "Screenshot of the network device management system settings demonstrating that third party devices are blocked from connecting to the Vodafone LAN. Where applicable, screenshot of blocked connections from non-Vodafone owned devices to LAN."},
        ],
    },
    {
        "control_id": "GENERAL_005",
        "control_name": "Customer Premises Equipment security",
        "vodafone_standard": "Tier 3 Customer Premises Equipment (CPE) Security Technical Standard [MR7]",
        "domain": "General",
        "d_statements": [
            {"id": "D1", "text": "For Consumer CPEs, default PSK must be generated randomly and uniquely for each CPE. In particular, the default PSK must not be derived from parameters that an attacker could determine e.g. from the CPE’s MAC address or a secret key shared by multiple CPEs."},
            {"id": "D2", "text": "For Consumer CPEs, default PSK must be at least 16 character long (alphanumeric case sensitive)."},
            {"id": "D3", "text": "For Consumer CPEs, in order to reduce the attack surface, unused services (i.e. open ports with listening processes) must be disabled by default on all interfaces."},
            {"id": "D4", "text": "For Consumer CPEs, the following security controls must be implemented to protect the CPEs against DoS and password bruteforcing:   - Password bruteforcing against the WebUI login page must be prevented by implementing increasing timeouts upon failed login attempt.  - CPEs must maintain normal operation for all protocols (at all layers) it supports independently on whether the traffic conforms to protocol specification or not."},
            {"id": "D5", "text": "For Consumer CPEs, for management services exposed on the WAN interface, the connection must be secured by strong protocols (e.g. TLS) with strong cipher suites and strong authentication."},
            {"id": "D6", "text": "For Consumer CPEs, the private key and corresponding public key certificate used by the TLS connection must be sufficiently random , and the private key must be kept confidential.   It must be possible to update the TLS private key and certificate via the secure management interface.   The end user must not be able to update the WAN interface TLS private key and certificate."},
            {"id": "D7", "text": "For Consumer CPEs, telnet must be disabled on all interfaces. It must not be used to manage the CPEs locally or remotely."},
            {"id": "D8", "text": "For Consumer CPEs, WebUI services must be exposed on LAN-side management interface only. Indeed, management access via WebUI must not be exposed on WAN management interface.  Authentication checks must be in place for all URLs of the WebUI.  It must not be possible for the user to disable authentication checks for the WebUI application.   Protection measures must be in place for all common web application vulnerabilities that allows authentication bypass and other abuses (CSRF, Session Fixation, XSS, Brute Force Attacks, etc.).   Sessions to the management WebUI must be terminated after a maximum idle time of 10 minutes."},
            {"id": "D9", "text": "For Consumer CPEs, a randomly generated default local WebUI password specific to each CPE must be provisioned in factory and printed on a label attached to the CPE itself (e.g. alongside the random default Wi-Fi PSK). It must be possible for the user to change this default WebUI password.     FOR EXISTING PRODUCTS NOT COMPLIANT TO THIS REQUIREMENT, PLEASE CHECK MR38"},
            {"id": "D10", "text": "For Consumer CPEs, the default password and any subsequent password selected by the user must be at least 8 characters long (alphanumeric)."},
            {"id": "D11", "text": "For Consumer CPEs, for existing products that cannot be compliant with"},
            {"id": "D12", "text": "For Consumer CPEs, TLS 1.2 [2] (or later versions) must be used to transport the CPE WAN Management Protocol (CWMP) between the ACS and the CPEs. TLS 1.2 (or later versions) must be used for files transfer between the CPE and a file server."},
            {"id": "D13", "text": "For Consumer CPEs, the CPE must authenticate the ACS using the ACS-provided certificate (i.e. server-side certificate)."},
            {"id": "D14", "text": "For Consumer CPEs, CPE to CPE management traffic must not be allowed. Only the authorized ACS can reach the CPEs’ TR-069 port, and only authorized CPEs can reach the ACS’ TR-069 port. This can be achieved by deploying filtering rules on the Broadband Network Gateway (BNG) (or, alternatively on the CPE) and on the firewall in front of the ACS."},
            {"id": "D15", "text": "For All CPEs:  For Consumer CPEs: Compliance with all remaining Mandatory Requirements in the Customer Premises Equipment (CPE) Security Technical Standard.  For Enterprise CPEs: Compliance with all Mandatory Requirements in the Router Hardening Principles Technical Standard."},
            {"id": "D16", "text": "For All New CPEs - Secure by Design Principle:  Prior to CPE procurement, confirm with suppliers that ALL newly procured CPEs can support the list of hardening requirements for both Consumer and Enterprise CPEs.  Configuration of New CPEs must comply with the hardening requirements prior to being provided to the customer or when connected for the very first time."},
        ],
        "e_statements": [
            {"id": "E1", "text": "Local Market/Entity: CPE vendor must evidence the software(s) and process(es) used to generate the PSK. The evidence must demonstrate how the PSK is generated and that the PSK is not derived from parameters that an attacker could determine."},
            {"id": "E2", "text": "Local Market/Entity: Picture of the CPE label that displays the PSK."},
            {"id": "E3", "text": "- Local Market/Entity: WAN side - port scan results (e.g. nmap)   - Local Market/Entity: LAN side - port scan results (e.g. nmap). In order to perform this test, a laptop with nmap scanner installed can be connected to the CPE to run an nmap scan."},
            {"id": "E4", "text": "- Local Market/Entity: Evidence (e.g. screenshot or video) showing the increasing timeout functionality upon failed login attempt. Evidence of configuration of this functionality  .    - Local Market/Entity: Evidence showing that CPEs maintain normal operation for all protocol supported (at all layers) independently on whether the traffic confirm to protocol specification or not."},
            {"id": "E5", "text": "Local Market/Entity: A \".pcap\" file (e.g. obtained with WireShark, as in"},
            {"id": "E12", "text": "), including IP packets of the security protocol(s) used in the WAN-exposed management services."},
            {"id": "E6", "text": "- Local Market/Entity: Evidence describing the process(es) and tools used to generate the TLS connection private/public key. The evidence should demonstrate that the private and public keys are sufficiently random.    - Local Market/Entity: Evidence describing where the entity stores the private key and what security mechanism is used to protect it.    - Local Market/Entity: Evidence describing the process used to update the TLS private key and certificate via the secure management interface and show how this is achieved.  - Local Market/Entity: Evidence shpwing that end users are not able to update the WAN interface TLS private key and certificate."},
            {"id": "E7", "text": "(covered by E3)"},
            {"id": "E8", "text": "- Local Market/Entity: Authentication check for http:// can be validated by"},
            {"id": "E10", "text": ". Screenshot of WebUI Login page for https:// (if used). The screenshot must show that an authentication check is in place.    - Local Market/Entity: Evidence from CPE vendorcovering the protection measures that are in place for all common web application vulnerabilities (CSRF, Session Fixation, XSS, Brute Force Attacks, etc.).    - Local Market/Entity: Evidence (e.g. a screenshot or video) showing the WebUI after 10 minutes of inactivity. The screenshot must show that the session is terminated.      Global Cyber Security will validate the following part of the requirement through the Umlaut test results:   \"WebUI services must be exposed on LAN-side management interface only. Indeed, management access via WebUI must not be exposed on WAN management interface\".    Entities not covered by Umlaut testing must show this themselves."},
            {"id": "E9", "text": "Local Market/Entity: Screenshot that shows the WebUI password change functionality  ."},
            {"id": "E11", "text": "- Local Market/Entity: Screenshot of the WebUI front page reminding customers with no unique password to set one.    - Local Market/Entity: Evidence showing that password reset to default is done via factory reset. If any other implementation for password recovery is used, the functionality should be evidenced confirming that it does not create any security vulnerabilities"},
            {"id": "E13", "text": "(covered by E12)"},
            {"id": "E14", "text": "Local Market/Entity: Global Cyber Security will validate this requirement based on the latest Umlaut test results. For entities not included in the Umlaut testing: Evidence showing how entity blocks CPE-to-CPE management traffic, e.g. a screenshot or an export of the filtering rule implemented on the BNG or CPE to comply with this requirement."},
            {"id": "E15", "text": "Local Market/Entity:​ Evidence demonstrating that Consumer and Enterprise CPE are meetings the remaining mandatory requirements described in their related standards."},
            {"id": "E16", "text": "- Local Market/Entity: Confirmation from supplier that newly procured CPEs can support the minimum baseline standards.  - Local Market/Entity: Evidence that new CPEs are being configured in line with the defined and approved minimum baseline standards e.g. configuration files.  - Local Market/Entity: Evidence of remediation actions undertaken for gaps found including risk assessments or compensating controls."},
        ],
    },
    {
        "control_id": "GENERAL_006",
        "control_name": "Detection of and response to Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS) attacks",
        "vodafone_standard": "",
        "domain": "General",
        "d_statements": [
            {"id": "D1", "text": "Managed objects have been constructed on the DDoS attack protection solution and provisioned for all critical services."},
            {"id": "D2", "text": "Specific reports are being run from the DDoS attack protection solution to indicate, e.g. how many times an attack has occurred and how many tests have been blocked. The reports are being reviewed and appropriate action is being taken in a timely manner."},
            {"id": "D3", "text": "The DDoS attack protection solution has been configured to send alerts to the teams responsible for the monitoring to allow real-time response."},
            {"id": "D4", "text": "Alerts from the solution are being investigated and acted upon by the support team in line with SLAs."},
            {"id": "D5", "text": "Checks are carried out to see if the support team have completed any required manual mitigations following receipt of alerts."},
            {"id": "D6", "text": "Automated mitigation has been enabled on the DDoS attack protection solution."},
            {"id": "D7", "text": "Appropriate checks are carried out by Service Owners to ensure that any changes, i.e. to replace a device, are following an agreed process to minimise the risk of an outage and the impacts of the change are fully understood."},
            {"id": "D8", "text": "Key documentation to support the DDoS attack protection solution such as policies, processes, procedures, service descriptions and high / low level designs have been created and/or updated as required for development and change projects to support the BAU phase and later (security) assessments."},
        ],
        "e_statements": [
            {"id": "E1", "text": "Screenshots from the DDoS attack protection solution demonstrating that IP address ranges for all critical networks and services are included in managed objects which trigger mitigation activities as appropriate. Alternatively, relevant documentation or on-boarding checklists which cover the managed objects."},
            {"id": "E2", "text": "Screenshot or copy of report from the DDoS attack protection solution demonstrating the number of attacks recorded and number of attacks blocked. Screenshots of review and follow up actions in accordance with documented processes, e.g. closure of alerts, incident tickets, trend analysis reports and suggestions for improvement."},
            {"id": "E3", "text": "Screenshot of one DDoS alert recorded on the DDoS attack protection solution and displayed / sent to the responsible monitoring team."},
            {"id": "E4", "text": "Copy of SLA for alerts. Screenshot of open alerts from the solution. Evidence that the alerts are being investigated and followed up by the support team in line with SLAs, e.g. support tickets or documented approval of exceptions. Where there are no open alerts, evidence that closed alerts have been resolved within specified SLAs."},
            {"id": "E5", "text": "Screenshot demonstrating that DDoS-related alerts are reviewed, with manual mitigation actions completed by the support team, before alerts are closed. Where checks reveal that manual mitigations were not completed, support tickets or email correspondence to put the manual mitigations in place."},
            {"id": "E6", "text": "Screenshot from the DDoS attack protection solution demonstrating that automated mitigation is enabled."},
            {"id": "E7", "text": "Checklist or process documentation demonstrating that all changes to web-facing systems and devices undergo appropriate change control to minimise the risk of an outage. Example of a change ticket documenting the impact assessment of the change, risk acceptance by the service owner."},
            {"id": "E8", "text": "Copies of documentation pertaining to the DDoS attack protection solution - policies, processes, procedures, service descriptions, design documents, maintenance and security assessments."},
        ],
    },
    {
        "control_id": "GENERAL_007",
        "control_name": "Mobile Backhaul Security",
        "vodafone_standard": "Tier 3 Mobile Backhaul [CYBER/STD/068] MR2 and MR58 to MR65",
        "domain": "General",
        "d_statements": [
            {"id": "D1", "text": "IPsec has been deployed to protect the Iub interface for all picocell and femtocell deployments. IPsec is implemented in accordance with requirements MR2 and MR58 to MR65 as defined in the Vodafone Tier 3 Mobile Backhaul Security version 1.07 or higher."},
            {"id": "D2", "text": "IPsec has been deployed to protect the S1-MME and S1-U interfaces (4G backhaul) and N2 and N3 interfaces (5G backhaul). IPsec is implemented in accordance with requirements MR4 and MR58 to MR65 as defined in the Tier 3 Mobile Backhaul Security version 1.07 or higher."},
            {"id": "D3", "text": "IPsec has been deployed to protect the X2 and Xn interfaces between 4G/5G RAN nodes. IPsec is implemented in accordance with requirements MR5 and MR58 to MR65 as defined in the Tier 3 Mobile Backhaul Security version 1.07 or higher."},
            {"id": "D4", "text": "IPsec has been deployed to protect the S1-U interface (4G backhaul) and N3 interface (5G backhaul) where these interfaces are terminated at a SGW-U or UPF in a MEC environment. IPsec is implemented in accordance with requirements MR7 and MR58 to MR65 as defined in the Tier 3 Mobile Backhaul Security version 1.07 or higher."},
            {"id": "D5", "text": "IPsec or DTLS has been deployed to protect the F1-C, W1-C and E1 interfaces (4G and 5G midhaul). Protection of these interfaces is mandatory if exposed to the transport network, even between co-located servers (e.g. at a cell site). IPsec is implemented in accordance with requirements MR8, MR9, MR48, MR49 and MR58 to MR65 as defined in the Tier 3 Mobile Backhaul Security version 1.07 or higher."},
            {"id": "D6", "text": "Packet-based fronthaul networks for 4G and 5G must be physically secured, and all equipment connected to the fronthaul network must be authenticated and authorised in line with requirements MR11 and MR12 as defined in the Tier 3 Mobile Backhaul Security version 1.07 or higher."},
            {"id": "D7", "text": "Where RAN sharing is implemented (either active or passive), each MNOs traffic must be segregated - including 4G and 5G mobile backhaul traffic (S1, N2, N3) and inter-eNB/gNB traffic (X2, Xn). Separate IPsec tunnels must be used for each MNO. Where interfaces are terminated by a SeGW, traffic for Vodafone subscribers must be terminated on a Vodafone SeGW. Overall, requirements MR13 to MR22 as defined in the Tier 3 Mobile Backhaul Security version 1.07 or higher must be met."},
            {"id": "D8", "text": "Where active RAN sharing is implemented and another MNO is providing the RAN for Vodafone subscribers, the RAN provider must meet certain requirements from Vodafone's Radio Tier 3 - namely those relating to Confidentiality and Integrity Protection (MR30 to MR58) and vulnerability management (MR59). Overall, requirement MR23 as defined in the Tier 3 Mobile Backhaul Security version 1.07 or higher must be met."},
            {"id": "D9", "text": "Security events are logged and stored centrally. Access to security logs is restricted to privileged accounts in line with requirement MR31 as defined in the Tier 3 Mobile Backhaul Security version 1.07 or higher."},
            {"id": "D10", "text": "L2 and L3 transport networks are hardened and ensure the segregation of management traffic from control and user plane traffic in line with requirements MR32 to MR37 as defined in the Tier 3 Mobile Backhaul Security version 1.07 or Higher."},
            {"id": "D11", "text": "Where IPsec is deployed for mobile backhaul, the RAN nodes and SeGW shall mutually authenticate using PKI certificates from an operator PKI platform. Accordingly, certificate lifecycle management protocols and processes must be implemented in line with requirements MR38 to MR44 as defined in the Tier 3 Mobile Backhaul Security version 1.07 or higher."},
            {"id": "D12", "text": "OSS and O&M (management plane) traffic is segregated from control and user plane traffic at the transport level, and secured end-to-end using appropriate protocols. The OSS and O&M systems can only be reached via the required protocols in line with requirements MR1, MR3, MR6, MR10, MR14 and MR24 to MR26 as defined in the Tier 3 Mobile Backhaul Security version 1.07 or higher."},
            {"id": "D13", "text": "TLS has been securely implemented in line with requirements MR27, MR45, MR46 and MR47 as defined in the Tier 3 Mobile Backhaul Security version 1.07 or higher."},
            {"id": "D14", "text": "DTLS has been securely implemented in line with requirements MR28, MR48 and MR49 as defined in the Tier 3 Mobile Backhaul Security version 1.07 or higher."},
            {"id": "D15", "text": "NETCONF/RESTCONF has been securely implemented in line with requirements MR29 and MR50 to MR53 as defined in the Tier 3 Mobile Backhaul Security version 1.07 or higher."},
            {"id": "D16", "text": "SSHv2 has been securely implemented in line with requirements MR30 and MR54 to MR57 as defined in the Tier 3 Mobile Backhaul Security version 1.07 or higher."},
        ],
        "e_statements": [
            {"id": "E1", "text": "Either a declaration that there are no 3G small cells deployed OR a 3G small cell design showing the Iuh interface carried over IPsec. IPsec may be terminated on a standalone SeGW, or a SeGW embedded with the HNB GW. Configuration evidence must be provided for all IPsec endpoints, to demonstrate compliance with the following aspects of MR60 and MR61:   • IKE version (v2)   • IKE endpoint certificate type (algorithm and key length)   • IKE authentication method (must be digital signature)   • IKE re-authentication frequency (i.e. max IKE session lifetime)   • IKE DH, PRF, authentication and encryption algorithms (demonstrating that the highest priority supported algorithms from MR60 are configured)   • IPsec (ESP) authentication and encryption algorithms (demonstrating that the highest priority supported algorithms from MR60 are configured)   • IPsec (ESP) SA lifetime   • PFS enabled  If multiple algorithms are configured, then the priority order must comply with MR60. In addition to showing IPsec endpoint configuration, the evidence could display the parameters associated with active IPsec tunnels.  An explanation must be provided of how the IKE re-authentication requirement in MR61 is met- e.g. RAN nodes will proactively trigger the re-authentication process, or RAN nodes will reactively use auth_liftime notifications from SeGW to trigger the process. In the former case the RAN nodes should have a shorter lifetime than the SeGW configured, and in the latter case the SeGW should have a shorter lifetime than the RAN configured.  If evidence provided is a sample from one or more nodes, then please explain which mechanism is used to ensure that the same configuration is applied to all nodes - e.g. EMS applies a common configuration baseline to all nodes."},
            {"id": "E2", "text": "Network design showing the deployment of geographically redundant SeGWs between the 4G/5G RAN and Core network. IPsec configuration evidence should be provided (as described in"},
            {"id": "E3", "text": "Network design showing X2 and Xn interfaces (where applicable) transported via IPsec tunnels. These IPsec tunnels may be \"direct\" between RAN nodes, or \"tromboned\" via the central SeGW). IPsec configuration evidence should be provided (as described in"},
            {"id": "E4", "text": "Either a declaration that MEC is not deployed OR a network diagram showing the use of IPsec to protect user plane interfaces between the RAN and MEC environment. IPsec configuration evidence should be provided (as described in"},
            {"id": "E5", "text": "Either a declaration that the F1, E1 and W1 (midhaul) interfaces are not implemented (or at least never exposed on the transport network), OR a network diagram showing that any midhaul interfaces are protected using IPsec or DTLS. Where IPsec is used, IPsec configuration evidence should be provided (as described in"},
            {"id": "E6", "text": "Description of the physical security mechanisms used to protect the fronthaul interface. Documentation from the RAN vendor describing the mechanism for authenticating equipment connected to the fronthaul network - e.g. IEEE 802.1X, or a proprietary solution."},
            {"id": "E7", "text": "Either a declaration that no RAN sharing is deployed OR high level design material for each RAN sharing solution. The design material should clearly show: a) which operators act as the RAN providers/consumers, b) the type of RAN sharing arrangement (e.g. passive, MORAN, MOCN), c) the scope (2G/3G/4G/5G), and d) the use of separate VRFs and IPsec tunnels to segregate 4G/5G traffic for each operator over the backhaul network (S1, X2, N2, N3 and Xn interfaces), and e) how 2G/3G traffic is split in the BSC/RNC and protected between operators. Any exception to this requirement must be declared. So far as permitted by 3GPP standards, plaintext traffic for Vodafone customers must not be visible to other network operators."},
            {"id": "E8", "text": "Umlaut (or equivalent) radio interface security assessments (drive tests and stationary tests)."},
            {"id": "E9", "text": "Security logging design, showing sources, destinations and transfer protocols. AAA log collection may be centralised, e.g. using a TACACS server. RAN node log collect may be centralised, e.g. using RAN Element Manager platform."},
            {"id": "E10", "text": "Description of backhaul transport solution(s) being used - e.g. L2 or L3 VPN. For L3 VPNs, evidence of CP/UP and O&M traffic segregation using VRFs. For L2 VPNs, evidence of CP/UP and O&M traffic segregation using VLANs."},
            {"id": "E11", "text": "Description of which operator PKI platform is used to issue certificates for the RAN nodes and SeGWs, and how the initial operator PKI certificate is issued (e.g. auto-enrolment using CMPv2). Evidence of automated certificate renewal using CMPv2 on RAN nodes and SeGW. Evidence of certificate revocation checking enabled on RAN nodes and SeGW."},
            {"id": "E12", "text": "RAN OSS design, listing all RAN OSS/O&M endpoints, protocols and protocol versions. Design showing OSS/O&M systems protected by a stateful firewall. Design showing dedicated VRFs and VLANs used to carry OSS/O&M traffic, with traffic carried either inside or outside of an IPsec tunnel. Design showing the use of mutual authentication and secure transport for all OSS/O&M interfaces."},
            {"id": "E13", "text": "Documentation from the RAN vendor(s) listing the TLS endpoints that are exposed via the mobile backhaul network (e.g. for OSS or O&M purposes). Where applicable, evidence or vendor declaration(s) that TLS 1.0 and TLS 1.1 are not supported/enabled, and that TLS 1.2 / TLS 1.3 ciphers are configured according to 3GPP 33.210."},
            {"id": "E14", "text": "Documentation from the RAN vendor(s) listing the DTLS endpoints that are exposed via the mobile backhaul network (e.g. for the 3GPP midhaul interfaces), or a declaration from the RAN vendor(s) that DTLS is not supported/enabled. Where applicable, configuration evidence that DTLS 1.2 ciphers are configured according to 3GPP 33.210."},
            {"id": "E15", "text": "Documentation from the RAN vendor(s) listing the NETCONF/RESTCONF endpoints that are exposed via the mobile backhaul network (e.g. for OSS or O&M purposes), OR a declaration from the RAN vendor(s) that NETCONF/RESTCONF is not supported/enabled. Where applicable, evidence showing that a secure transport protocol is used (TLS or SSHv2). Where applicable, evidence that a least privilege access control model has been implemented using NACM."},
            {"id": "E16", "text": "Documentation from the RAN vendor(s) listing the SSHv2 endpoints that are exposed via the mobile backhaul network (e.g. for OSS or O&M purposes), or a declaration from the RAN vendor(s) that SSHv2 is not supported/enabled. Where applicable, evidence that all SSHv2 endpoints are configured to use SSH keys or X.509 certificates for authentication, and that SSHv2 clients cannot authenticate using passwords. Where applicable, evidence that SSHv2 endpoints support only strong algorithms (aligned with Mozilla \"Intermediate\" or \"Modern\" profiles)."},
        ],
    },
