    {
        "control_id": "IR_001",
        "control_name": "Information security events and incidents management",
        "vodafone_standard": "",
        "domain": "IR",
        "d_statements": [
            {"id": "D1", "text": "Management responsibilities and procedures are established to support a quick, effective and orderly response to information security incidents. Supporting procedure and guidance documents are approved by management, published and communicated to employees and relevant external parties, covering  - incident response planning and preparation;  - monitoring, detecting, analysing and reporting of information security events and incidents;  - logging incident management activities;  - handling of forensic evidence;  - assessment of and decision on information security events and assessment of information security weaknesses; and  - response including those for escalation, controlled recovery from an incident and communication to internal and external people or organisations in line with legal requirements."},
            {"id": "D2", "text": "The procedures are being reviewed on a regular basis or ad hoc e.g. to factor in learnings from previous information security incidents and updated as required."},
            {"id": "D3", "text": "Contracts with third-parties that have access to Vodafone systems and / or data include detailed security incident requirements that support the organisation's information security incident management approach."},
            {"id": "D4", "text": "Personnel involved in responding to and managing security incidents have the necessary skills and receive ongoing training on the organisation's incident response and management processes, procedures and tools as well as changes of the threat landscape to ensure incidents are managed effectively and in a timely manner."},
            {"id": "D5", "text": "The Group Cyber Security Incident Management Global Standard v3.0 or later, OR equivalent approved local version has been implemented."},
            {"id": "D6", "text": "The workforce's knowledge about where and how to report potential security incidents is being refreshed on a regular basis through awareness campaigns / messages as appropriate."},
            {"id": "D7", "text": "The security incident response team are staffed and available 24/7 x 365/6 to respond to security incidents."},
            {"id": "D8", "text": "A management escalation process is followed in the event of a serious security incident or escalation of an incident to a higher priority and to keep senior management up-to-date for serious incidents."},
            {"id": "D9", "text": "Systems are monitored and alerts generated based on specified criteria; an automated response ensures service tickets are raised to appropriate support teams and actioned based on severity."},
            {"id": "D10", "text": "A formal process assists to help identify security incidents and detail the necessary steps to be taken to reach that decision."},
            {"id": "D11", "text": "Formal evidence is being produced / captured to document that events have been processed in line with the defined process."},
            {"id": "D12", "text": "Mechanisms and processes are in place to ensure that possibly important events aren't being missed and get processed in a timely manner."},
            {"id": "D13", "text": "Incident forms / checklists are used depending upon incident type to ensure pertinent details are captured and kept and reporting/notification timescales can be met."},
            {"id": "D14", "text": "A retention policy is implemented that covers the relevant types of information and time period it needs to be retained to assist with security incident investigations."},
            {"id": "D15", "text": "The Cyber Security Incident Management Global Standard policy has been communicated to relevant staff and is being followed."},
            {"id": "D16", "text": "Formal procedures that provide advice on how to respond to security incidents have been defined and communicated to relevant staff and third-parties, covering  - collecting evidence in a timely manner;  - conducting information security forensics analysis, as required;  - escalation, as required;  - external notification, as required;  - logging all involved response activities with date / time stamps for later analysis;  - communicating the existence of the information security incident or any relevant details thereof to other internal and external people or organisations as needed;  - dealing with information security weakness(es) found to cause or contribute to the incident; and  - formally closing the incident and recording it once it has been successfully dealt with."},
            {"id": "D17", "text": "The procedures define incident priority levels and corresponding target response and escalation times to support a consistent approach and measuring / improving the effectiveness of the approach."},
            {"id": "D18", "text": "A crisis/major incident process that details the approach and steps to be taken to assist in serious security incidents has been defined, documented and communicated to the relevant stakeholders, including clear decision criteria of what falls into this category and related decision making mechanisms."},
            {"id": "D19", "text": "Dedicated formal processes and procedures have been defined, documented and communicated to the relevant staff to support cases where a forensic investigation is required to support a consistent approach and ensure that evidence captured can't be tampered with, and a second copy has been made for further analysis."},
        ],
        "e_statements": [
            {"id": "E1", "text": "Copy of document covering information security incident identification and response procedures, including escalation points and accountabilities. Evidence that the procedures have been made available to relevant stakeholders e.g. it is available on the company intranet or as part of awareness training materials"},
            {"id": "E2", "text": "Document provided in E1 contains a revision history that clearly shows the review dates to demonstrate it has been regularly updated. Supporting correspondence/documents where available (e.g. meeting minutes/agenda items) that demonstrates learnings from previous incidents have been included in the procedures."},
            {"id": "E3", "text": "Extract of a contract with third party supplier with access to Vodafone systems which includes information security incident management procedures in line with policy requirements, e.g. incident resolution and root cause analysis SLAs."},
            {"id": "E4", "text": "Copy of incident management training and awareness materials, copy of staff competency or training records for personnel with incident management responsibilities."},
            {"id": "E5", "text": "Copy of audit report or policy compliance review performed against Group Cyber Security Incident Management Global Standard v3.0 or later, OR evidence that local information security incident management policies are aligned with Group requirements e.g. incident classification levels, KPIs, RACI."},
            {"id": "E6", "text": "Copy of incident management training and awareness materials for staff with no direct incident management responsibilities (i.e. staff not covered by sample in E4]. Copy of process documentation for staff awareness training e.g. frequency of training, information requirements. Evidence that there is a straightforward method for staff to access the incident reporting channel or contact details on the intranet, e.g. a screenshot of search results for 'report security incident' or equivalent."},
            {"id": "E7", "text": "Copy of security incident response team on-call schedules."},
            {"id": "E8", "text": "Copy of process document covering escalation of security incidents to management. Screenshot of a security incident ticket demonstrating investigations taken and escalation processes, including communication to senior management."},
            {"id": "E9", "text": "Screenshot of central monitoring system for identifying potential and actual security incidents, including criteria for generating alerts. Screenshot of automated response service tickets sent to appropriate teams, and evidence of investigation or actions taken."},
            {"id": "E10", "text": "Copy of process document covering identification of security incidents, with specific extracts or page references for decision making guidance."},
            {"id": "E11", "text": "Screenshots of a security incident ticket demonstrating processes are being followed as per E10."},
            {"id": "E12", "text": "Documentation or screenshot demonstrating that events which are not escalated into security incidents are reviewed at regular intervals to ensure possibly important events are not being missed OR evidence that monitoring systems for identifying incidents are regularly updated with new incident criteria."},
            {"id": "E13", "text": "Copy of incident report capturing incident timelines, actions taken and notifications to stakeholders e.g. senior management, affected customers, suppliers."},
            {"id": "E14", "text": "Copy of policy document covering types of information required for security or forensic investigation and retention periods. Documented record that forensic data which has exceeded its retention period is securely deleted."},
            {"id": "E15", "text": "Evidence that awareness and training materials provided in E4 and E6 are aligned with Cyber Security Incident Management Global Standard policy."},
            {"id": "E16", "text": "Copy of document covering incident management procedures which have been communicated to (a) staff and (b) relevant third parties with access to Vodafone systems and data. Provide specific extracts or page references. Evidence that this procedure document is included in contracts with third parties (refer to E3) OR evidence that third party incident management processes have been reviewed and are confirmed to be aligned with Vodafone's requirements."},
            {"id": "E17", "text": "Copy of procedure document defining incident priority levels and KPIs for response and escalation, with specific extracts or page references."},
            {"id": "E18", "text": "Copy of policy document specifying crisis management processes including escalation points and accountabilities (note: this may be covered in document supplied for E1). Evidence of communications to key stakeholders and decision makers."},
            {"id": "E19", "text": "Copy of policy or process document specifying requirements for forensic investigations, evidence that this document is made available to relevant support staff."},
        ],
    },
    {
        "control_id": "DATA_004",
        "control_name": "Privacy and protection of personally identifiable information",
        "vodafone_standard": "Tier 3 Protecting Personal Information (CYBER/STD/004) MR1",
        "domain": "Data",
        "d_statements": [
            {"id": "D1", "text": "Pseudonymisation must be applied to the personal data processing scenarios listed in Tier 3 Protecting Personal Information Section 3.1 Pseudonymisation General Rules."},
            {"id": "D2", "text": "Anonymisation must be applied to the scenarios listed in Tier 3 Protecting Personal Information Section 3.2 Anonymisation – General Rules."},
            {"id": "D3", "text": "Re-identification of pseudonymous data can only happen under the conditions listed in Tier 3 Protecting Personal Information Section 3.3 Re-identification"},
            {"id": "D4", "text": "The likelihood of unauthorised re-identification must be evaluated through a risk assessment. See Tier 3 Protecting Personal Information Section 3.4 Risk of re-identification and 3.5 Risk assessment methodology."},
            {"id": "D5", "text": "Reversible Pseudonymisation: Where data from multiple controllers is processed in the same environment (e.g. Group Analytics Platform used by multiple local markets), it must be possible for each controller to have their own re-identification key, allowing only the re-identification of its own data, and not that of another controller. Keys are different for different sets of data (i.e. many different keys instead of one key for all local market data)"},
            {"id": "D6", "text": "Pseudonymisation: Effective technical and organisational controls must be implemented to ensure that the key required to re-identify the data is kept strictly separate from those who process the data (e.g. data analysts do not have access to the re-identification keys), and access to the keys is strictly restricted."},
            {"id": "D7", "text": "Effective technical and organizational controls are implemented to prevent unauthorized or accidental re-identification of the Pseudonymous data."},
            {"id": "D8", "text": "Anonymous insights: For Use Cases which are intended to result in anonymous insights, the output may only contain aggregated and anonymous statistical information."},
            {"id": "D9", "text": "Pseudonymisation: For analytical platforms where the required business use cases require different fields to be linked or associated, the minimum requirement for data to be entered into the platform is pseudonymisation."},
            {"id": "D10", "text": "If the proposed processing falls into a category covered by the use cases in Tier 3 Protecting Personal Information Section 7 then section 7 guidance must be followed, otherwise the general steps described in Tier 3 Protecting Personal Information Sections 3 - 5."},
        ],
        "e_statements": [
            {"id": "E1", "text": "Screenshot or process document of pseudonymisation of personally identifiable information in the following scenarios:   i. sharing personal data with a data processor;   ii. transferring personal data of EU based individuals outside of the EEA;  iii. processing production data in non-production environment;  iv. in scenarios where it is unnecessary for all users to have the same level of access to personal data."},
            {"id": "E2", "text": "Screenshot or process document of anonymisation of personally identifiable information in the following scenarios -  i. where appropriate consent is difficult to obtain for new purpose of processing data;   ii. where single records containing personal data must be disposed and data deletion may result in loss of data integrity;  iii. there is a business need to use data for research, statistical, reporting or analytic purposes;  iv. there is a business need to share data with third parties for there independent needs/purposes;   v. processing in non-production environments where it is NOT necessary to re-identify individuals."},
            {"id": "E3", "text": "Documentation containing details of security measures which control re-identification of psuedonymised data, showing re-identification is prevented, unless the conditions listed in Section 3.3 of the Protecting Personal Information Standard are met."},
            {"id": "E4", "text": "Documented risk assessment covering likelihood and impact of unauthorised reversal of de-identification, controls in place, and management acceptance of risk."},
            {"id": "E5", "text": "Document containing details of security measures to prevent multiple controllers accessing data not owned by them, and screenshots of how they access data their own data."},
            {"id": "E6", "text": "Copy of process document covering key management for re-identification of data, which meets the requirement."},
            {"id": "E7", "text": "Document containing details of security measures to prevent unauthorised re-identification of de-identified data, which is formally approved by management."},
            {"id": "E8", "text": "Confirmation that the personally identifiable information is securely disposed and cannot be reconstructed from the data subject's records e.g. data flow diagram or screenshots. Screenshots evidencing the data only contains aggregated and anonymous statistical information."},
            {"id": "E9", "text": "Copy of process documentation for de-identification process for analytical platforms confirming the minimum technique applied is pseudonymisation."},
            {"id": "E10", "text": "Where the use case falls into the categories identified in Section 7 (MR10) of the standard - evidence that the guidance is followed."},
        ],
    },
    {
        "control_id": "CHG_001",
        "control_name": "Compliance of systems with hardening standards",
        "vodafone_standard": "Tier 2 SSMP (CYBER_038) Section 5.2 Server and Client Configuration AND Section 5.4 Network Storage Systems",
        "domain": "CHG",
        "d_statements": [
            {"id": "D1", "text": "Formally documented and approved Minimum Configuration Standards for operating systems, databases and networks are defined, documented approved and published. The standards are being reviewed on a regular basis and updated as required."},
            {"id": "D2", "text": "The configuration of new systems is being checked against the defined Minimum Configuration Standards prior to the go live date. A risk assessment is being performed for deviations from the Minimum Configuration Standards found, followed by a remediation (e.g. through patching, system upgrades or configuration changes), the implementation of compensating controls and / or following a risk acceptance process as required before the system goes live."},
            {"id": "D3", "text": "The configuration of systems in production is being checked against the defined Minimum Configuration Standards on an ongoing basis. A risk assessment is being performed for deviations from the Minimum Configuration Standards found, followed by a remediation (e.g. through patching, system upgrades or configuration changes), the implementation of compensating controls and / or following a risk acceptance process as required."},
        ],
        "e_statements": [
            {"id": "E1", "text": "Evidence of approved and reviewed minimum configuration standards. Where local standards are produced these must be in line with or exceed the requirements of the Group minimum configuration standard."},
            {"id": "E2", "text": "Evidence that systems are being checked against the minimum configuration standards prior to go live and that any deviations found are risk assessed, remediated or compensated for prior to deployment. Evidence of the risk acceptance process where it has not been possible to remediate or compensate."},
            {"id": "E3", "text": "Evidence of variations from the minimum defined configuration standards are checked for and identified on an ongoing basis. Reporting showing that deviations have been addressed through remediation or compensation. Evidence of the risk acceptance process where it has not been possible to remediate or compensate."},
        ],
    },
